title: Introduction to tsgp
text: tsgp lightweight package modelling univariate time-series data Gaussian processes (GP). important remember using GP time series basically converts problem one modelling generative process (e.g., used ARIMA model) essentially curve-fitting exercise. GPs Bayesian method, unfamiliar Bayesian inference, please go check resources , great video Richard McElreath. Essentially, key bits remember post Bayesian inference, interested posterior distribution, proportional product prior (beliefs event seeing data) likelihood (probability data given model parameters). like deeper treatment GPs can model time-series data, please see post.

title: Introduction to tsgp
text: going simulate time series data temporal dynamics commonly encountered applied settings. Specifically, going generate noisy sine wave (.e., emulate periodic seasonal data) linearly increasing trend:
code: set.seed(123) y <- 3 * sin(2 * seq(0, 4 * pi, length.out = 100)) + runif(100) * 2 trend <- 0.08 * seq(from = 1, to = 100, by = 1) y <- y + trend tmp <- data.frame(timepoint = 1:length(y), y = y) x1 <- 1:length(y)  # Draw plot  ggplot(data = tmp) +   geom_point(aes(x = timepoint, y = y), colour = "black") +   geom_line(aes(x = timepoint, y = y), colour = "black") +   labs(x = "Timepoint",        y = "Values") +   theme_bw()

title: Introduction to tsgp
text: tsgp contains several covariance functions (coded C++ efficiency). return object class GPCov (just matrix new inherited class allows us make use R‚Äôs generic functions).

title: Introduction to tsgp
text: \[ k(x, x') = \text{exp} \left( -\frac{1}{2\sigma^{2}}||x - x'||^{2} \right) \] tsgp, cov_exp_quad takes following arguments: xa ‚Äî vector values xb ‚Äî vector values sigma ‚Äî scalar denoting variance. Defaults 1 l ‚Äî scalar denoting lengthscale. Defaults 1 can produce two types plots GPCov objects calling plot() generic. first plot samples prior distribution, specify setting type = "prior", passing input vector (x2 example), setting number samples draw argument k. example:  second plot covariance matrix represented heatmap:
code: x2 <- seq(from = -2, to = 2, length.out = 100) mat_exp_quad <- cov_exp_quad(x2, x2, 1, 1) plot(mat_exp_quad, x2, type = "prior", k = 5) plot(mat_exp_quad, type = "matrix")

title: Introduction to tsgp
text: \[ k(x, x') = \sigma^{2} \left( 1 + \frac{||x - x'||^{2}}{2\alpha \mathcal{l}^{2}} \right)^{-\alpha} \] tsgp, cov_rat_quad takes following arguments: xa ‚Äî vector values xb ‚Äî vector values sigma ‚Äî scalar denoting variance. Defaults 1 alpha ‚Äî scalar \(>0\) denoting mixing coefficient. Defaults 1 l ‚Äî scalar denoting lengthscale. Defaults 1
code: mat_rat_quad <- cov_rat_quad(x2, x2, 1, 1, 1) plot(mat_rat_quad, x2, type = "prior", k = 5) plot(mat_rat_quad, type = "matrix")

title: Introduction to tsgp
text: \[ k(x, x') = \sigma^{2} \text{exp} \left( -\frac{2}{\mathcal{l}^{2}}\text{sin}^{2} \left( \pi\frac{|x - x'|}{p} \right) \right) \] tsgp, cov_periodic takes following arguments: xa ‚Äî vector values xb ‚Äî vector values sigma ‚Äî scalar denoting variance. Defaults 1 l ‚Äî scalar denoting lengthscale. Defaults 1 p ‚Äî scalar denoting period. Defaults 1
code: mat_periodic <- cov_periodic(x2, x2, 1, 1, 1) plot(mat_periodic, x2, type = "prior", k = 5) plot(mat_periodic, type = "matrix")

title: Introduction to tsgp
text: \[ k(x,x') = \sigma^{2}_{b} + \sigma^{2}_{v} (x‚àíc)(x'‚àíc) \] tsgp, cov_linear takes following arguments: xa ‚Äî vector values xb ‚Äî vector values sigma_b ‚Äî scalar denoting constant variance. Defaults 1 sigma_v ‚Äî scalar denoting constant variance. Defaults 1 c ‚Äî scalar denoting offset. Defaults 1
code: mat_linear <- cov_linear(x2, x2, 1, 1, 1) plot(mat_linear, x2, type = "prior", k = 5) plot(mat_linear, type = "matrix")

title: Introduction to tsgp
text: \[ k(x, x') = \sigma^{2}I_{n} \] tsgp, noise handled within core GP function since applies covariance matrix observations. GP function discussed later vignette. However, visual comparison covariance functions, looks like:
code: cov_noise <- function(x, sigma = 0.5){   X <- sigma * diag(length(x))   X <- structure(X, class = c("GPCov", "matrix"))   return(X) }  mat_noise <- cov_noise(x2, 0.5) plot(mat_noise, x2, type = "prior", k = 5) plot(mat_noise, type = "matrix")

title: Introduction to tsgp
text: Often time-series analysis need models capture multiple different statistical dynamics simultaneusly, trend, seasonality, noise. quite easy define custom composite kernel function either sums multiplies different kernels:
code: CovSum <- function(xa, xb, sigma_1 = 1, sigma_2 = 1, l_1 = 1, l_2 = 1, p = 1){   X <- cov_exp_quad(xa, xb, sigma_1, l_1) +      cov_periodic(xa, xb, sigma_2, l_2, p)      X <- structure(X, class = c("GPCov", "matrix"))   return(X) }

title: Introduction to tsgp
text: core function tsgp calculate posterior mean vector covariance matrix GP. GP returns object class TSGP list input data, posterior mean vector, posterior covariance matrix. GP takes following arguments: x ‚Äî vector input data xprime ‚Äî vector data points predict values y ‚Äî vector values learn covfun ‚Äî function specifying covariance noise ‚Äî scalar denoting noise variance add \((x, x)\) covariance matrix observations. Defaults 0 noise modelling ... ‚Äî hyperparameters passed cov_function example model predicts values set uniformally-distributed time points \([1-100]\) domain:
code: mod <- GP(x1, seq(from = 1, to = 100, by = 5), y, CovSum, noise = 0.8,            sigma_1 = 5, sigma_2 = 1, l_1 = 75, l_2 = 1, p = 25)  names(mod) #> [1] "x"      "xprime" "y"      "mu"     "Sigma"

title: Introduction to tsgp
text: can easily visualise draws posterior distribution calling plot() TSGP object. plot() generic TSGP takes three arguments: x ‚Äî TSGP model object prob ‚Äî desired credible interval probability level. Defaults 0.95 \(95\%\) credible interval draws ‚Äî number posterior draws summarise . Defaults \(100\) example:  another model predicts time points \(1000\) draws:  Need uncertainty?  short-range forecast?

text: can install development version tsgp GitHub using following:
code: devtools::install_github("hendersontrent/tsgp")

title: Simple Time Series Modelling Using Gaussian Processes
text: tsgp implements functionality presented recent tutorial modelling time-series data Gaussian processes. Currently, univariate setting supported. tsgp works structural time series perspective. , decomposing time series constituent statistical parts (e.g., trend, seasonality, noise), one can model component independently combining form complete picture temporal dynamics. intuitive, also highly transparent‚Äîmeaning intelligent justifiable modelling decisions must made order appropriately capture data generating process. tsgp extremely lightweight dependencies computational approach. seeking rigorous flexible approach using GPs time-series analysis, please look Stan, GPy, GauPro, Tensorflow Probability, GaussianProcesses.jl.

title: Simple Time Series Modelling Using Gaussian Processes
text: Currently, tsgp supports following covariance functions (kernels): Exponentiated quadratic (squared exponential) Rational quadratic Periodic Linear tsgp flexibly enables composite kernels (either addition multiplication) constructed actively encouraged appropriately model complex temporal dynamics. tsgp also includes functions computing visualising draws Gaussian process priors posteriors, visualising covariance matrices, plotting predictions.

title: Simple Time Series Modelling Using Gaussian Processes
text: tsgp extremely fast . Well, fast can given ùí™(N3) computation time inverting matrix involved fitting GP. full model trend, seasonality, noise can calculated time series T‚ÄÑ=‚ÄÑ1000 time points seconds. makes ideal tool iterative model building principled time-series exploration.
